<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-convergence-tests-for-series"
xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Convergence Tests for Series</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="sec-series"/> we defined convergence of a series and
      proved the divergence test (<xref ref="prop-divergence-test-series"/>).
      Here we develop positive tests that help us decide whether a series
      converges.
    </p>

    <p>
      A series <m>\sum x_n</m> is called a <term>Cauchy series</term><idx>Cauchy
      series</idx> if its sequence of partial sums is a Cauchy sequence. By
      <xref ref="prop-convergent-implies-cauchy"/> and
      <xref ref="thm-sequential-completeness-of-reals"/>, a series of real
      numbers converges if and only if it is Cauchy.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-geometric">
    <title>Geometric Series</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-geometric-series">
      <title>Geometric Series</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>r\in\R</m>. The geometric series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty r^n
          </me>
          converges to <m>1/(1-r)</m> when <m>|r|&lt;1</m>, and diverges when
          <m>|r|\ge 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>s_k=\sum_{n=0}^k r^n</m>. If <m>r\ne 1</m>, then
          <me>
            (1-r)s_k = (1-r)(1+r+r^2+\cdots+r^k)=1-r^{k+1},
          </me>
          so
          <me>
            s_k=\frac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r}.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
	  Suppose first that <m>|r|&lt;1</m>. Then <m>|r^n| = |r|^n
	  \to 0</m> by <xref ref="prop-geometric-sequence-test"/> and so
	  <m>(r^n)</m> is null. Therefore, <m>s_k\to 1/(1-r)</m>,
	  and the series converges to that value.
	</p>

        <p>
          If <m>|r| \ge 1</m>, then <m>|r^n|\ge 1</m> for all <m>n</m>,
          so <m>r^n</m> is not a null sequence. Thus, the series diverges
          by <xref ref="prop-divergence-test-series"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-geometric-series-basic">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Taking <m>r=1/3</m> gives
          <me>
            1+\frac13+\frac19+\frac1{27}+\cdots
            =
            \frac{1}{1-\frac13}
            =
            \frac32.
          </me>
          Taking <m>r=-1/2</m> gives
          <me>
            1-\frac12+\frac14-\frac18+\cdots
            =
            \frac{1}{1+\frac12}
            =
            \frac23.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-positive-terms">
    <title>Series with Nonnegative Terms</title>

    <p>
      For a series with nonnegative terms, the sequence of partial sums is
      automatically increasing. This gives a useful criterion.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-nonnegative-series-criterion">
      <title>Nonnegative Term Criterion</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n\ge 0</m> for all <m>n</m>. Then the series
          <m>\sum x_n</m> converges if and only if its sequence of partial sums
          is bounded above.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>s_k=\sum_{n=1}^k x_n</m>. Since each <m>x_n\ge 0</m>, we have
          <m>s_{k+1}-s_k=x_{k+1}\ge 0</m>, so <m>(s_k)</m> is increasing. An
          increasing sequence converges if and only if it is bounded above by
          <xref ref="thm-monotone-convergence"/>. Since the series converges
          exactly when <m>(s_k)</m> converges, the result follows.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-harmonic-series-diverges">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The harmonic series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n}
          </me>
          diverges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Group the terms as
          <me>
            1+\frac12+\left(\frac13+\frac14\right)+
            \left(\frac15+\frac16+\frac17+\frac18\right)+\cdots.
          </me>
          For each <m>k\ge 1</m>, the block from <m>n=2^k+1</m> to
          <m>n=2^{k+1}</m> has <m>2^k</m> terms, and each of those terms is at
          least <m>1/2^{k+1}</m>. Hence each block has sum at least
          <m>1/2</m>. Therefore the partial sums are unbounded above, so the
          series diverges by <xref ref="prop-nonnegative-series-criterion"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </example>

    <p>
      The previous example is the basic comparison for the
      <term><m>p</m>-series</term><idx>p-series</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-p-series-test">
      <title><m>p</m>-Series Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For <m>p\in\R</m>, the series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^p}
          </me>
          converges if and only if <m>p&gt;1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          If <m>p\le 1</m>, then <m>1/n^p \ge 1/n</m> for all <m>n\in\N</m>.
          Hence every partial sum of <m>\sum 1/n^p</m> is at least as large as
          the corresponding partial sum of the harmonic series. Since the
          harmonic series diverges by
          <xref ref="eg-harmonic-series-diverges"/>, the series
          <m>\sum 1/n^p</m> also diverges.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now suppose <m>p&gt;1</m>. For each <m>k\ge 0</m>, every
          <m>n</m> with <m>2^k\le n \lt 2^{k+1}</m> satisfies
          <m>1/n^p \le 1/(2^k)^p</m>. Therefore
          <me>
            \sum_{n=2^k}^{2^{k+1}-1}\frac{1}{n^p}
            \le
            2^k\frac{1}{(2^k)^p}
            =
            2^{k(1-p)}.
          </me>
          Since <m>0\lt 2^{1-p}\lt 1</m>, the geometric series
          <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty 2^{k(1-p)}</m> converges by
          <xref ref="prop-geometric-series"/>. Hence the partial sums of
          <m>\sum 1/n^p</m> are bounded above, and so the series converges by
          <xref ref="prop-nonnegative-series-criterion"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      Another important notion is <term>absolute convergence</term><idx>absolute
      convergence</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-absolute-convergence-implies-convergence">
      <title>Absolute Convergence Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If the series <m>\sum |x_n|</m> converges, then the series
          <m>\sum x_n</m> converges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>u_k=\sum_{n=1}^k |x_n|</m> and <m>s_k=\sum_{n=1}^k x_n</m>.
          Since <m>(u_k)</m> converges, it is Cauchy by
          <xref ref="prop-convergent-implies-cauchy"/>. If <m>m&gt;n</m>, then
          <md>
	  <mrow>
            |s_m-s_n|
            &amp; =
            |x_{n+1}+x_{n+2}+\cdots+x_m|
	  </mrow>
	  <mrow>
            &amp; \le
            |x_{n+1}|+|x_{n+2}|+\cdots+|x_m| = u_m-u_n.
	  </mrow>
          </md>
          Hence <m>(s_k)</m> is also Cauchy. By
          <xref ref="thm-sequential-completeness-of-reals"/>, the sequence
          <m>(s_k)</m> converges, so <m>\sum x_n</m> converges.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-comparison-tests">
    <title>Comparison Tests</title>

    <p>
      The first comparison tool is the <term>comparison test</term><idx>comparison
      test for series</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-comparison-test-series">
      <title>Comparison Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>0\le x_n\le y_n</m> for all <m>n</m>. If
          <m>\sum y_n</m> converges, then <m>\sum x_n</m> converges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>s_k=\sum_{n=1}^k x_n</m> and <m>t_k=\sum_{n=1}^k y_n</m>.
          Then <m>0\le s_k\le t_k</m> for every <m>k</m>. If <m>\sum y_n</m>
          converges, then <m>(t_k)</m> is bounded above. Consequently
          <m>(s_k)</m> is bounded above as well, and
          <xref ref="prop-nonnegative-series-criterion"/> shows that
          <m>\sum x_n</m> converges.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      A useful refinement is the <term>limit comparison test</term><idx>limit
      comparison test</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-comparison-test-series">
      <title>Limit Comparison Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n&gt;0</m> and <m>y_n&gt;0</m> for all <m>n</m>. If
          <me>
            \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{x_n}{y_n}=L
          </me>
          for some <m>L&gt;0</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> converges if and only if
          <m>\sum y_n</m> converges.
        </p>
        <p>
          If instead
          <me>
            \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{x_n}{y_n}=0,
          </me>
          then convergence of <m>\sum y_n</m> implies convergence of
          <m>\sum x_n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First suppose <m>L&gt;0</m>. Then for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>
          <me>
            \frac{L}{2} \lt \frac{x_n}{y_n} \lt \frac{3L}{2}
          </me>
          Since <m>y_n&gt;0</m>, this is equivalent to
          <me>
	  \frac{L}{2}y_n \lt x_n \lt \frac{3L}{2}y_n.
          </me>
	  
	  If <m>\sum y_n</m> converges, then so does <m>\sum (3L/2)y_n</m>, and
	  the comparison test gives convergence of <m>\sum x_n</m>. Conversely,
	  if <m>\sum x_n</m> converges, then so does <m>\sum (2/L)x_n</m>,
	  and the comparison test applied to <m> y_n \lt (2/L)x_n </m>
	  shows that <m>\sum y_n</m> converges.
	</p>

        <p>
          If <m>x_n/y_n\to 0</m>, then for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>
          <m>x_n/y_n&lt;1</m>. Hence <m>0\lt x_n\lt y_n</m> eventually,
          so convergence of <m>\sum y_n</m> implies convergence of <m>\sum
          x_n</m> by the comparison test.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-limit-comparison-n-cubed-minus-one">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{1}{n^3-1}
          </me>
          converges. Indeed,
          <me>
            \lim_{n\to\infty}
            \frac{\frac{1}{n^3-1}}{\frac{1}{n^3}}
            =
            \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{n^3}{n^3-1}
            =
            1,
          </me>
          and <m>\sum 1/n^3</m> converges by
          <xref ref="prop-p-series-test"/>. Therefore
          <m>\sum 1/(n^3-1)</m> converges by
          <xref ref="prop-limit-comparison-test-series"/>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-ratio-root-tests">
    <title>Ratio and Root Tests</title>

    <p>
      The next tests compare a series to a geometric series. The first is
      the <term>ratio test</term><idx>ratio test for series</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-ratio-test-series">
      <title>Ratio Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>(x_n)</m> be a sequence of real numbers such that
          <m>x_n\ne 0</m> for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>, and suppose
          <me>
            \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{|x_{n+1}|}{|x_n|}=L.
          </me>
          If <m>L&lt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> converges absolutely. If
          <m>L&gt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> diverges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>L&lt;1</m>. Then <m>L\lt r:=(1+L)/2 \lt 1</m>, so for all
	  <m>n</m> sufficiently large,
          <me>
	  \frac{|x_{n+1}|}{|x_n|}\lt r.
          </me>

	  By dropping finitely many terms, which does not affect convergence,
	  we can assume the inequality holds for all <m>n</m>. Hence,
          <md>
            <mrow>
              |x_2| &lt; |x_1|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              |x_3| &lt; r|x_2| &lt; r^2|x_1|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \vdots
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
	    |x_n| &lt; r^{n-1}|x_1|.
            </mrow>
          </md>
	  Since <m>0 \lt r \lt 1</m>, <m>\sum r^k</m> converges by <xref
	  ref="prop-geometric-series"/> and the comparison test implies that
	  <m>\sum_{n=N}^\infty |x_n|</m> converges. Therefore <m>\sum x_n</m>
	  converges absolutely.
	</p>

        <p>
          Now suppose <m>L&gt;1</m>, and set <m>r=(1+L)/2</m>. Then
          <m>1\lt r\lt L</m>, so there exists <m>N</m> such that
          <m>|x_{n+1}|/|x_n| \gt r\gt 1</m> for all <m>n\ge N</m>. In
          particular, <m>|x_n|</m> is eventually strictly increasing, so it
          cannot converge to <m>0</m>. Therefore <m>\sum x_n</m> diverges by
          <xref ref="prop-divergence-test-series"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-ratio-test-series-polynomial-over-exponential">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n^2}{2^n}
          </me>
          converges absolutely, because
          <me>
            \frac{(n+1)^2/2^{n+1}}{n^2/2^n}
            =
            \frac{(n+1)^2}{2n^2}
            \to
            \frac12.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      If the ratio limit is <m>1</m>, the ratio test gives no conclusion:
      both <m>\sum 1/n</m> and <m>\sum 1/n^2</m> have consecutive-term ratio
      tending to <m>1</m>, but the first diverges and the second converges.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <term>root test</term><idx>root test for series</idx> is often more
      convenient when the <m>n</m>-th power is explicit.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-root-test-series">
      <title>Root Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <me>
            L=\limsup_{n\to\infty}|x_n|^{1/n}.
          </me>
          If <m>L&lt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> converges absolutely. If
          <m>L&gt;1</m>, then <m>\sum x_n</m> diverges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
	<p> Suppose <m>L&lt;1</m>, then for some <m>N</m> sufficiently
	large, 
	<me>
	      \sup_{n \ge N} |x_n|^{1/n} &lt; r := \frac{1+L}{2} &lt; 1.
	</me> 

	That means <m>|x_n| &lt; r</m> for all sufficiently large
	<m>n</m>.  Since <m>0 &lt; r &lt; 1, \sum r^n</m> converges and,
	by the comparison test, so does <m>\sum |x_n|</m>.
	</p>

        <p>
	Now suppose <m>L&gt;1</m>. Then for all sufficiently large <m>N</m>,

	<me>
              \sup_{n \ge N} |x_n|^{1/n} &gt; r := \frac{1+L}{2} &gt; 1.
	</me>
	
	Thus, <m>1</m> is not an upper bound of the set <m>\{|x_n|^{1/n}
	\colon n \ge N\}</m>. And so there exists <m>n \ge N</m> such that
	<m>|x_n|^{1/n} &gt; r</m>. That means <me>
	   |x_n| &gt; r^n &gt; 1
	</me> for infinitely many <m>n</m>. As a result <m>(x_n)</m> cannot
	be a null sequence and <m>\sum x_n</m> is divergent by
	  <xref ref="prop-divergence-test-series"/>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p> Later, we will see that the Root Test is strictly more powerful than
    the Ratio Test.  </p>
    
    <example xml:id="eg-root-test-series-nth-power">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left(\frac{3n}{4n+1}\right)^n
          </me>
          converges absolutely, because
          <me>
            \left|\left(\frac{3n}{4n+1}\right)^n\right|^{1/n}
            =
            \frac{3n}{4n+1}
            \to
            \frac34
            &lt;
            1.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The root test is also inconclusive when <m>L=1</m>. For example,
      <m>\sum 1/n</m> diverges while <m>\sum 1/n^2</m> converges, but both
      satisfy <m>\lim |x_n|^{1/n}=1</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-series-alternating">
    <title>Alternating Series</title>

    <p>
      The final test in this section is the <term>alternating series
      test</term><idx>alternating series test</idx>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-alternating-series-test">
      <title>Alternating Series Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>x_n\ge 0</m> for all <m>n</m>, the sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is
          decreasing, and <m>x_n\to 0</m>. Then the alternating series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty (-1)^{n+1}x_n
          </me>
          converges.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>s_k=\sum_{n=1}^k (-1)^{n+1}x_n</m>. Then
          <me>
            s_{2k+2}-s_{2k}=x_{2k+1}-x_{2k+2}\ge 0,
          </me>
          so the even partial sums form an increasing sequence. Also,
          <me>
            s_{2k+3}-s_{2k+1}=-x_{2k+2}+x_{2k+3}\le 0,
          </me>
          so the odd partial sums form a decreasing sequence.
        </p>

        <p>
          For every <m>k</m>, we have <m>s_{2k}\le s_{2k+1}\le s_1=x_1</m>.
          Thus <m>(s_{2k})</m> is increasing and bounded above, so it converges
          by <xref ref="thm-monotone-convergence"/>. Write
          <m>s_{2k}\to L</m>. Since
          <me>
            s_{2k+1}-s_{2k}=x_{2k+1}\to 0,
          </me>
          the limit laws imply that <m>s_{2k+1}\to L</m> as well. Therefore
          the whole sequence of partial sums converges to <m>L</m>, and the
          series converges.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-alternating-harmonic-series">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The alternating harmonic series
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}
          </me>
          converges by <xref ref="prop-alternating-series-test"/>, because
          <m>(1/n)</m> is decreasing and null. It is not absolutely convergent,
          since
          <me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left|\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}\right|
            =
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n}
          </me>
          diverges. Hence it is conditionally convergent.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The proof shows more: if <m>L=\sum_{n=1}^\infty (-1)^{n+1}x_n</m>, then
      the error after <m>n</m> terms satisfies
      <me>
        |L-s_n|\le x_{n+1}.
      </me>
      So the first omitted term controls the truncation error.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      References: compare <xref ref="biblio-lebl-basic-analysis"/>,
      Sections 2.5-2.6, for a treatment close to the organization of this
      section, <xref ref="biblio-rudin-pma"/>, Chapter 3, for a more concise
      treatment, and <xref ref="biblio-rosenlicht-intro"/> for additional
      worked examples.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
